     80935 M■nchen
     GERMANY

   Support and online registration is available at @{b}http://www.sasg.com/@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "BackMan" "BackMan_eng.guide/BackMan"
@toc "Main"

BackMan
*******

   BackMan is a stand-alone shell program, which was developed in order to
give you a small command that is able to backup and restore your data even
in emergency situations.


 @{" Command Line Arguments " link "Command Line Arguments"}

   BackMan has few options when compared to the MUI/GUI version.  The
shell version is intended mainly for emergency restore actions; normally
you should use BackManMUI (see @{"BackManMUI" link "BackManMUI"}), which has lots of options and
facilities.  The shell version can also be useful for unattended
operations.

   BackMan does also listen to a couple of keypresses when it is running:

   * Press @{b}<CTRL>+C@{ub} to abort BackMan.

   * Press @{b}<CTRL>+F@{ub} to stop (pause) BackMan; press @{b}<CTRL>+F@{ub} again to
     restart.


@endnode

@node "Command Line Arguments" "BackMan_eng.guide/Command Line Arguments"
@toc "BackMan"

Command Line Arguments
======================

   You can choose which operation to perform with the @{b}RESTORE@{ub}, @{b}COMPARE@{ub},
@{b}DIFF@{ub} or @{b}LIST@{ub} switches.  By default BackMan will backup the directory
specified by the @{b}DIR@{ub} argument (or the current directory if none is
specified).

   You must specify one of @{b}SCSI_DEVICE@{ub}, @{b}DRIVE@{ub} and @{b}FILE@{ub} to indicate which
medium you want to use for the backup.

   Here is a description of all the command line arguments:

@{b}DIR/M@{ub}
     specify directory to backup or restore.

     You can specify more than one directory:

        - if you are creating a new backup, each directory will be backed
          up on a separate catalog;

        - if you are restoring a backup, each directory name you specify
          will become the destination of a catalog on the backup: if
          catalogs exceed specified directories, the original directory
          names (saved on the backup) will be used; if directories exceed
          catalogs, they will simply be ignored.

@{b}PAT=PATTERN@{ub}
     select files to backup or restore.

     This is a standard AmigaDOS wildcard pattern for selecting which
     files you want to backup or restore.

@{b}SCSI_DEVICE/K@{ub}
@{b}SCSI_ID/K/N@{ub}
@{b}SCSI_LUN/K/N@{ub}
     specify SCSI tape streamer's device, ID and LUN.

@{b}     SCSI_DEVICE@{ub} indicates the name of the Exec-level SCSI device the
     streamer is connected to: typical choices are @{b}scsi.device@{ub} for most
     Commodore SCSI hostadapters, @{b}gvpscsi.device@{ub} for GVP SCSI cards, etc.

@{b}     SCSI_ID@{ub} and @{b}SCSI_LUN@{ub} indicate the SCSI ID and logical unit of your
     tape streamer: they default to 5 and 0, respectively.  The SCSI ID is
     typically configured by jumpers or switches on the peripheral: please
     refer to the peripheral's manual for more details.  The SCSI logical
     unit (LUN) is almost always 0, so you shouldn't need to explicitly
     set it: again, see the peripheral's manual.

@{b}DRIVE/K@{ub}
     drive name(s) (such as @{b}DF0:@{ub}, @{b}PC0:@{ub}, etc.).

     Doesn't need trailing colon, but will be truncated at the first colon
     if present (i.e. you could say @{b}DF0:foo@{ub} if you really wanted to).

@{b}FILE/K@{ub}
     name of the file to read/write.

@{b}RES=RESTORE/S@{ub}
     instructs BackMan to restore your data.

     See @{"Restore" link "Restore"}, in the chapter regarding BackManMUI.

@{b}CMP=COMPARE/S@{ub}
     instructs BackMan to compare the data on the backup with those on your
     hard disk.

     See @{"Compare" link "Compare"}, in the chapter regarding BackManMUI.

@{b}DIFF/S@{ub}
     instructs BackMan to compare the data on the backup with those on your
     hard disk, in a way faster than the above.

     See @{"Diff" link "Diff"}, in the chapter regarding BackManMUI.

@{b}LIST/S@{ub}
     reads file catalogs from the backup and prints them, without
     restoring data.

     The @{b}LIST@{ub} switch automatically enables the @{b}VERBOSE@{ub} switch (see below)
     and does nothing else. Only selected entries will be shown.

@{b}LINKS/S@{ub}
     backup/restore hard links too.

@{b}EMPTY=EMPTYDRAWERS/S@{ub}
     backup/restore empty drawers too.

@{b}SHOW=VERBOSE/S@{ub}
     print file catalogs before the operation starts.

     The @{b}LIST@{ub} option (see above) automatically enables this switch and
     does nothing else. Only selected entries will be shown.

@{b}OWNER/S@{ub}
     backup/restore file owner information.

@{b}ARC=ARCHIVEBIT/S@{ub}
     set the @{b}archived@{ub} bit of backed up files.

@{b}NV=NOVERIFY/S@{ub}
     don't verify floppy disks as they are written.

@{b}NF=NOFORMAT/S@{ub}
     don't format floppy disks.

@{b}NFA=NOFMTALL/S@{ub}
     don't format the empty part of the last floppy disk.

@{b}NC=NOCOMMENT/S@{ub}
     don't restore file comment.

     See @{"Restore options" link "Restore options"}, in the chapter regarding BackManMUI.

     Please note that this option refers to files' comments, while the
     next refers to the global backup comment. Don't confuse the two
     things.

@{b}COM=COMMENT/K@{ub}
     specify backup comment.

     This comment will be shown every time the backup is read. By default,
     the comment will be set to the name of the drawer being backed up.

@{b}CRE=CREATOR/K@{ub}
     specify backup creator's name.

@{b}XPK=PACKER/S@{ub}
     specify XPK packer to use.

     You must specify a string of the form @{b}FAST.42@{ub}, where @{b}FAST@{ub} is the
     packer's name and @{b}42@{ub} is the desired efficiency.

@{b}CRYPTER/S@{ub}
     specify XPK crypter to use.


@endnode

@node "BackManMUI" "BackMan_eng.guide/BackManMUI"
@toc "Main"

BackManMUI
**********

   BackManMUI is the main program of this package. Once you start it, you
will see some informations and some buttons which enable you to do all the
magic...


Here are the buttons and the relative actions:
 @{" Backup                   " link "Backup"}  Backup your files...
 @{" Restore                  " link "Restore"}  ...and restore them.
 @{" Compare                  " link "Compare"}  See what's changed...
 @{" Diff                     " link "Diff"}  ...in two different manners.

 @{" Configure...             " link "Configuration"}  But set up some things first!

   The @{b}About...@{ub} and @{b}Quit@{ub} buttons at the bottom of the window should not
need further explanation.

   The same functions are available through the pull-down menus.

   Also, BackManMUI can be driven from ARexx. See @{"Rexx commands" link "Rexx commands"}.

Notes on the User Interface
===========================

   * Most of the requesters displayed by BackManMUI do not provide keyboard
     shortcuts for the buttons, contrary to common practice: this is a
     choice, not a mistake. During a backup, it could happen that a
     requester pops up to inform the user of some problem while he is
     doing something else: if the user was typing something on the
     keyboard, he could inadvertently answer the requester, with
     potentially disastrous results.

     The requester buttons, however, can be activated with the <TAB> key
     and then selected with <RETURN>. You can also select the rightmost
     button (usually meaning a negative response) by pressing the <ESC>
     key.


@endnode

@node "Configuration" "BackMan_eng.guide/Configuration"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Configuration
=============

   You should configure BackManMUI before proceeding further.

   After you have selected the @{b}Configure...@{ub} button, you will be presented
a window containing two @{i}register groups@{ui}:

   * the one at the top enables you to set up various options, described in
     @{"General options" link "General options"}, @{"Backup options" link "Backup options"}, @{"Restore options" link "Restore options"},
     @{"Compare options" link "Compare options"}, @{"File selection options" link "File selection options"};

   * the one at the bottom, described in @{"Backup device" link "Backup device"}, enables you to set
     up the backup device that BackManMUI will use.

   At the bottom of the window there are the usual @{b}Save@{ub}, @{b}Use@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub}
buttons. Through the pull-down menus, you can also save the current
options with another name (@{b}Save As...@{ub}) or load a previously saved set of
options (@{b}Load...@{ub}).


@endnode

@node "General options" "BackMan_eng.guide/General options"
@toc "Configuration"

General options
---------------

   Select the appropriate checkboxes to activate the following options:

@{b}Handle file owner@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to backup/restore file owner information. This
     option is selectable only if you have @{b}muFS@{ub} installed; if you don't
     have @{b}muFS@{ub}, this option isn't of much interest for you, anyway.

@{b}     Please note:@{ub} With @{b}muFS@{ub} only @{b}root@{ub} can restore file owner information.

@{b}Iconify after Start@{ub}

@endnode

@node "Backup options" "BackMan_eng.guide/Backup options"
@toc "Configuration"

Backup options
--------------

   Select the appropriate checkboxes to activate the following options:

@{b}Set 'archived' bit@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to set the @{b}archived@{ub} bit on the backed up files. The
     bit will be set only if the backup finished successfully (this is a
     sort of security check).

@{b}Backup hard links@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will backup hard links as they are. If not
     selected, hard links will be backed up just like a normal file (i.e.
     the backup will take more space, especially if the link is a
     directory).

     A link is stored as the full path of the linked file, relative to the
     root of the volume it is on; the path is shown in the @{b}Comment@{ub} field
     in the file selection window (see @{"File selection" link "File selection"}).

@{b}     PLEASE NOTE@{ub}: Currently BackMan does not support soft links, because
     they are rarely used and even the operating system lacks full support
     for them.

@{b}Backup empty drawers@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to backup all the drawers, even if they are empty.

@{b}XPK Data Compression@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will compress the data using the configured XPK
     sub-library in order to save space. To select the XPK library, press
     the popup button on the right (see @{"XPK packer" link "XPK packer"}).

@{b}XPK Data Encryption@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will encrypt the data using the configured XPK
     sub-library in order to add some security to your backup. To select
     the XPK library, press the popup button on the right (see
     @{"XPK crypter" link "XPK crypter"}).


@endnode

@node "XPK packer" "BackMan_eng.guide/XPK packer"
@toc "Backup options"

XPK packer
..........

   You will access the XPK sub-library selection window by pressing the
appropriate popup button in the configuration window.

   In the left part of this window you will see a list of the available
XPK compression libraries. To the right, a short text displays some
informations about the currently selected library.

   You can set the packing mode (the efficiency) with the @{b}Mode@{ub} slider.
When you move this slider, the two gadgets below (which display the
(de)compression speed and the approximate compression ratio) will be
updated.


@endnode

@node "XPK crypter" "BackMan_eng.guide/XPK crypter"
@toc "Backup options"

XPK crypter
...........

   You will access the XPK sub-library selection window by pressing the
appropriate popup button in the configuration window.

   This window is quite similar to the @{b}XPK Packer@{ub} window, with some
changes: there is no compression ratio gauge, the list shows only XPK
crypters, and the (de)crypt speed is usually very low (consider this if
you are running BackMan on a slow system).

   The @{b}Mode@{ub} slider sets the security of the encrypted data: if you encrypt
your data with the @{b}IDEA@{ub} method and a security of 100, you may sleep
between two pillows...

   If you enable crypting, you will be asked for a password every time you
start a backup or a restore. @{b}WARNING@{ub}: there is no way to restore an
encrypted backup if you have forgotten the password!


@endnode

@node "Restore options" "BackMan_eng.guide/Restore options"
@toc "Configuration"

Restore options
---------------

   Select the appropriate checkboxes to activate the following options:

@{b}Restore 'archived' bit@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to restore also the @{b}archived@{ub} bit, along with the
     other flags.

@{b}Restore hard links@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will create hard links for files that were backed
     up as links. If not checked, such files will not be restored.

@{b}Restore empty drawers@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to restore also empty directories. If not checked,
     empty directories will not be created.

@{b}Restore file comment@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to restore file comments.

     Turning file comments off is especially useful when restoring files
     to a disk or partition handled by CrossDOS (or similar), since the
     CrossDOS file system doesn't support comments: you would get a @{b}Can't
     set comment@{ub} error for every file with a comment.

@{b}Existing files@{ub}
     Selecting the appropriate action you can replace, rename or skip an
     existing file during the restore action. If you select @{b}Ask@{ub}, BackMan
     will ask you what to do for every file that already exists.

     If you chose to rename an already existing file, you will be asked
     for a new file name by a requester entitled @{b}Enter new name@{ub}: you can
     skip the file by selecting the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button of the requester.


@endnode

@node "Compare options" "BackMan_eng.guide/Compare options"
@toc "Configuration"

Compare options
---------------

   Select the appropriate checkboxes to activate the following options:

@{b}Compare flags@{ub}

@{b}Compare file comment@{ub}

@endnode

@node "File selection options" "BackMan_eng.guide/File selection options"
@toc "Configuration"

File selection options
----------------------

@{b}Show extended protection bits@{ub}
     Displays also protection bits for @{b}Group@{ub} and @{b}Others@{ub} in the file
     selection window, in addition to the usual bits.  See @{"File selection" link "File selection"}.

     This option is useful only if you are working with @{b}muFS@{ub} or networking
     software such as Envoy, because the standard Amiga file systems don't
     make use of the extended protection bits.

@{b}Start with hidden drawers@{ub}
     Instructs BackMan to open the file selection window with all the
     subdirectories hidden (except those in the root directory).  See
     @{"File selection" link "File selection"}.


@endnode

@node "Backup device" "BackMan_eng.guide/Backup device"
@toc "Configuration"

Backup device
-------------

   You can set the backup medium that BackMan will use by selecting one of
the register group entries. You have three choices: tape streamer (see
@{"Tape" link "Tape"}), disks (see @{"Disk" link "Disk"}), and AmigaDOS file (see @{"File" link "File"}).


@endnode

@node "Tape" "BackMan_eng.guide/Tape"
@toc "Backup device"

Tape backup
...........

   To use a SCSI tape streamer with BackMan, you simply have to enter the
name of the SCSI device (usually @{b}scsi.device@{ub} for Commodore hostadapters
like the A590, the A2091, and A3000's built-in hostadapter) and the SCSI ID
and LUN of the tape drive.  BackMan will print the vendor and product
information of the given SCSI peripheral at the bottom of the
configuration window, so you can immediately see if you chose the correct
device, ID and LUN.

   The @{b}Rewind@{ub} button instructs BackMan to rewind the tape before every
operation. Deselect it for multiple backups on a single tape.

   The @{b}Verify@{ub} button is not implemented as of this version.

   The following table lists the hardware configurations on which
BackMan's tape handling has been tested and is known to work:

   * Commodore A3000's built-in SCSI hostadapter (@{b}scsi.device@{ub} 40.4)
        - Tandberg TDC 3660 tape streamer (DC6150 and DC6250 cartridges)

          Some older Tandberg firmware revisions can't write DC6150
          cartridges, some other can cause SCSI bus hang-ups. If you are
          using this streamer, please report which firmware revision you
          have and any problems you may have encountered.

   * Commodore A2091 SCSI hostadapter
        - Commodore A3070 Tape drive (Caliper)

   * ICD AdSCSI 2080 hostadapter (on an Amiga 4000)
        - Archive Viper 150A tape streamer (DC6150 cartridges)

   * Tekram DC-310 hostadapter (on Pegasos/MorphOS version)
        - Hewlett-Packard C1533A (DDS-2)

   You can also use your streamer through a tape device handler (like
@{b}BTNtape@{ub}, on Aminet), backing up on a file (see @{"File" link "File"}). Tapes written by
BackMan using Tape mode are compatible with tapes written using File mode
through BTNtape, but only if the backup fits on a single tape.


@endnode

@node "Disk" "BackMan_eng.guide/Disk"
@toc "Backup device"

Disk backup
...........

   You can choose which disk device BackMan will use by clicking on the
popup button near the text field on the left. Then, simply select the
drive and press the @{b}OK@{ub} button.

@{b}   WARNING@{ub}: don't select your hard disk as the backup device unless you
know very well what you're doing, or you might get really upset by the
results!

   There are also some options you can set via the usual checkboxes:

@{b}Format@{ub}
     Instruct BackMan to use the @{b}TD_FORMAT@{ub} command instead of the usual
     @{b}TD_WRITE@{ub} command when talking to the device. Floppy disk writes are
     faster with @{b}TD_FORMAT@{ub}, but some devices may not like being formatted,
     so here is this switch.

@{b}Format all tracks@{ub}
     This is available only if the previous option is active, and will
     force BackMan to format the remaining tracks on the last disk of the
     backup.

@{b}Verify@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan verifies each write, to assure that the backup
     media is reliable and that data has been written correctly.

     If you don't want bad surprises, leave this option active all the
     time!

   All disk devices that have a valid DOS device entry are supported: this
includes CrossDOS disks, Diskspare disks, hard disks (of which removable
cartridges like SyQuest drives are a subset) and most recoverable RAM
drives (we wouldn't recommend them as backup devices, however).  High
density floppies are supported, but you should insert an high density disk
before you start the backup; otherwise, BackMan will not read the correct
disk size.


@endnode

@node "File" "BackMan_eng.guide/File"
@toc "Backup device"

File backup
...........

   You can even do a backup on a single AmigaDOS file. The string gadget
to the left holds the default directory where backup files will be stored
and, optionally, the name of a default backup file (this depends on the @{b}Ask
filename@{ub} checkbox, see below).

   There are also some options you can set via the usual checkboxes:

@{b}Delete file on error@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will delete incomplete backup files if you abort
     the backup operation.

@{b}Ask filename@{ub}
     If checked, BackMan will pop up a file request when you start the
     backup/restore operation, to enable you to select a backup file name.
     If not checked, the filename present in the string gadget to the left
     will be used: in this case, the string gadget @{b}must@{ub} contain a valid
     file name!

   To use BTNtape with BackMan, you should set the string gadget to @{b}TAPE:@{ub}
and deselect the two checkboxes. This configuration has been tested with
an Amiga 4000, an A2091 SCSI card and an A3070 tape streamer.


@endnode

@node "Backup" "BackMan_eng.guide/Backup"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Backup
======

   When you select @{b}Backup@{ub} from the main window, a file requester will pop
up, asking you the directory you want to backup. Next, the file catalog
will be read, and the backup window will appear.

   Here you have a catalogs list and some buttons, along with some
informations on the total/selected files and dimension of the backup you
are going to start.  The catalogs are listed in the order they were read.
but you can sort it with drag'n'drop.

   As in other windows, actions can be chosen by using buttons or
pull-down menus.  Some actions are available only from menus. The actions
are:

@{b}Add...@{ub}
     BackMan can backup more than one catalog in a single backup set. With
     this button, you can add another catalog to the current backup. A file
     request will pop up, asking you for the directory to read the catalog
     from.

@{b}Remove@{ub}
     This button will remove the currently selected catalog from the
     backup. You will be asked for confirmation before proceeding.

@{b}Select files...@{ub}
     Selecting this button will open the file selection window for the
     currently selected catalog (see @{"File selection" link "File selection"}).  You can open the
     file selection window also by double-clicking on one of the first
     three columns of the catalogs list.

@{b}Comment...@{ub}
     You can change the comment associated with the current catalog by
     pressing this button. The same action can be obtained by
     double-clicking on the last column of the catalogs list.

@{b}Print...@{ub}
     This option, available only from pull-down menus, will print the
     currently selected catalogs to the printer or to a file. A file
     request will pop up, asking for a file name: if you select @{b}OK@{ub} without
     changing anything, the list will be printed, otherwise saved to the
     selected file (if you are using @{b}ReqChange@{ub} or other tools that patch
     @{b}asl.library@{ub} to use @{b}reqtools.library@{ub}, direct printing will not work --
     you are warned!).

@{b}Configure...@{ub}
     Only available from pull-down menus, this option will open the
     configuration window, to let you make last-moment changes to the
     configuration (see @{"Configuration" link "Configuration"}).

@{b}Creator@{ub}
     Here you can write the name of the backup creator: it will be saved
     in the backup. This field is used only for your reference.

   At last, when you have finished with initializations, you can select the
@{b}Start@{ub} button to start the backup, or the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button to go back to the
main window.


@endnode

@node "Restore" "BackMan_eng.guide/Restore"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Restore
=======

   When you select @{b}Restore@{ub} from the main window, a request will pop up
(depending on the backup medium you set via the configuration window)
asking you to do the appropriate things to make BackMan read the backup
catalogs. Next, the restore window will appear.

   Here you have a catalogs list and some buttons, along with some
informations on the total/selected files and dimension of the backup you
are going to restore.

   As in other windows, actions can be chosen by using buttons or
pull-down menus.  Some actions are available only from menus. The actions
are:

@{b}Include@{ub}
     This button will include all the files in the currently selected
     catalog for restoration.

@{b}Exclude@{ub}
     This button will exclude all the files in the currently selected
     catalog, thus they will be not restored.

@{b}Select files...@{ub}
     Selecting this button will open the file selection window for the
     currently selected catalog (see @{"File selection" link "File selection"}).  You can open the
     file selection window also by double-clicking on one of the last
     three columns of the catalogs list.

@{b}Destination@{ub}
     This option will let you select the destination path for the
     currently selected catalog. A file requester will pop up to allow you
     to select the new path. You can obtain the same action by
     double-clicking on the first column of the catalogs list.

@{b}Print...@{ub}
     This option, only available from pull-down menus, will print the
     currently selected catalogs to the printer or to a file. A file
     request will pop up, asking for a file name: if you select @{b}OK@{ub} without
     changing anything, the list will be printed, otherwise saved to the
     selected file (if you are using @{b}ReqChange@{ub} or other tools that patch
     @{b}asl.library@{ub} to use @{b}reqtools.library@{ub}, direct printing will not work --
     you are warned!).

@{b}Configure...@{ub}
     Only available from pull-down menus, this option will open the
     configuration window, to let you make last-moment changes to the
     configuration (see @{"Configuration" link "Configuration"}). The backup device register group
     will be ghosted, because you cannot change the backup medium at this
     point.

   At last, when you have finished with initializations, you can select the
@{b}Start@{ub} button to start the restore, or the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button to go back to the
main window.


@endnode

@node "Compare" "BackMan_eng.guide/Compare"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Compare
=======

   This window and the related buttons and menus are identical to those of
the restore window. The only difference is that files will not be
restored, but instead compared to their matching files on your hard disk:
this is very useful to discover which files have been changed since your
last backup.

   First, file attributes (date, comment, etc.) are compared; then, if the
file size was not changed, file contents are compared too. Any file which
differs in one or more attributes or in file contents, or which has been
deleted, will be reported.

   Refer to @{"Restore" link "Restore"} for more information.


@endnode

@node "Diff" "BackMan_eng.guide/Diff"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Differences
===========

   This window and the related buttons and menus are identical to those of
the restore window. The only difference is that files will not be
restored, but instead compared to their matching files on your hard disk
in a manner similar (faster, but less precise) to that of compare: files
will not be compared based on their contents, but only on their
attributes. Thus, there is no need for BackMan to read the whole backup,
but only the file catalog.

   Refer to @{"Restore" link "Restore"} and @{"Compare" link "Compare"} for more information.


@endnode

@node "File selection" "BackMan_eng.guide/File selection"
@toc "Backup"

File selection
==============

   At the top of the file selection window, you can find some useful
informations about the number of file and the size of the whole catalog
and of the included entries. Below, you can find two lists:

   The topmost list displays the @{i}directory tree@{ui} of the catalog. For each
directory, you can see some useful informations like the number of files
in that directory, and how much of them are selected for backup or
restore. Below the list there are some buttons which perform the following
actions:

@{b}Include Dirs@{ub}
     include all the files in the current directory and in all its
     subdirectories.

@{b}Exclude Dirs@{ub}
     exclude all the files in the current directory and in all its
     subdirectories.

@{b}Show/Hide@{ub}
     shows/hides the currently selected directory's contents: all its
     subdirectories will be hidden/revealed; hiding subdirectories is
     especially useful if you have a very deep directory tree.

     An hidden directory is indicated by a @{b}+@{ub} sign to the left of its name,
     while a shown directory is indicated by a @{b}-@{ub} sign; leaf directories
     have no sign at all.

     You can also show/hide directories by double-clicking on the first
     column of the directory entry (the one that shows the directory
     name). A double click on any other field will include/exclude
     (depending on the current state) the directory and all its contents.

@{b}Filter...@{ub}
     opens the filters window, that allows you to (de)select files using
     some filter fields. See @{"Filter" link "Filter"}.

   The list at the bottom displays the @{i}files@{ui} contained in the currently
selected directory. You can (de)select each file by clicking on it.
Multiple selection is also possible. Below the list there are some buttons
which perform the following actions:

@{b}All@{ub}
     select all files, for successive inclusion or exclusion.

@{b}None@{ub}
     deselect all files.

@{b}Include@{ub}
     include all the selected files.

     You can do the same thing by double-clicking on an excluded file.

@{b}Exclude@{ub}
     exclude all the selected files.

     You can do the same thing by double-clicking on an included file.


@endnode

@node "Filter" "BackMan_eng.guide/Filter"
@toc "File selection"

Filter
------

   Using the gadgets in the @{b}Filter@{ub} window, you can do some important
filtering actions on the current catalog. There are some checkmarks, often
followed by a string gadget where you can enter parameters for the filter.
At the bottom of the window there are the @{b}Include@{ub} and @{b}Exclude@{ub} buttons,
which will do the corresponding action on the files of the currently
selected directory.

   A complete description of each filter item follows:

@{b}'Archive' bit set/unset@{ub}
     exclude/include files with the @{b}archived@{ub} bit set/unset.

     Very useful for incremental backups.

@{b}Modified on or after@{ub}
     operate on files modified on or after the specified date.

     Date must be in the same format used by the @{b}List@{ub} command.

@{b}Modified on or before@{ub}
     operate on files modified on or before the specified date.

     Date must be in the same format used by the @{b}List@{ub} command.

@{b}Matching pattern@{ub}
     operate on files matching the specified pattern.

     You can use the normal AmigaDOS wildcards.

@{b}Apply to current drawer only@{ub}
     By default, the filter acts on the files of current directory and of
     all his subdirectories. If you check this option, inclusion/exclusion
     will be limited to the files of the current directory.

   The filter window is asynchronous, so you can keep it open while
working on the file selection window. The window will be automatically
closed when you close the file selection window.


@endnode

@node "Rexx commands" "BackMan_eng.guide/Rexx commands"
@toc "BackManMUI"

Rexx commands
=============

@{i}   <under construction>@{ui}

   This is a list of available Rexx commands:

@{b}BACKUP <dir>,...@{ub}
     Reads the specified directory or directories and opens the backup
     window.  See @{"Backup" link "Backup"}.

@{b}RESTORE <source>@{ub}
     Reads from the specified source and opens the Restore window.  See
     @{"Restore" link "Restore"}.

@{b}COMPARE <source>@{ub}
     Reads from the specified source and opens the Compare window.  See
     @{"Compare" link "Compare"}.

@{b}START@{ub}
@{b}PAUSE@{ub}
@{b}ABORT@{ub}
     These commands do exactly the same action as the corresponding
     buttons in the progress window, except that @{b}ABORT@{ub} does not ask for
     confirmation during unattended operation.

@{b}CONFIG@{ub}
     This command allows you to change the configuration:
    @{b}LOAD <filename>@{ub}
          Loads the configuration from the specified configuration file.

    @{b}SAVE <filename>@{ub}
          Saves the configuration to the specified configuration file.

    @{b}ITEM <id> [VALUE] <value>@{ub}
          Sets a configuration item to the specified value.

          Configuration items correspond to the options in the
          Configuration window.  Each checkmark, field, etc. has a
          specific four-letter ID (which is, by the way, the MUI object
          ID).

          For a table of available configuration items, see
          @{"Configuration items" link "Configuration items"}.

@{b}TAPE@{ub}
     This command allows you to control a tape drive from BackManMUI.
     There are several subcommands, which can be abbreviated as indicated:

    @{b}REWind@{ub}

    @{b}RETension@{ub}

    @{b}EJECT@{ub}
@{b}     PLEASE NOTE@{ub}: The @{b}ERASE@{ub} command is missing on purpose.  Believe me,
     you don't want to erase a tape during unattended operation.  And if
     you really want, use some other tool, for example BTNtape's @{b}tape.rexx@{ub}
     script.

@{b}QUIT@{ub}
@{b}HIDE@{ub}
@{b}SHOW@{ub}
     These commands are defined by MUI.  For a description of their
     meaning, please refer to @{"ARexx" link "MUI:Docs/English/MUI.guide/USE_AREXX"}.


@endnode

